"Fietz S., Kobanova G., Izmesteva L., Nicklisch A.","Regional, vertical and seasonal distribution of phytoplankton and photosynthetic pigments in Lake Baikal",2005,"Journal of Plankton Research","27","8",,"793","810",,,10.1093/plankt/fbi054,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-26844482930&partnerID=40&md5=64fd905cf82356e5d0811ce0bb84edf8","Leibniz Institute of Freshwater Ecology and Inland Fisheries, Mueggelseedamm 301, 12587 Berlin, Germany; Scientific Research Institute of Biology, State University Irkutsk, Lenina 3, 664003 Irkutsk, Russian Federation; Institute of Biology, Humboldt University Berlin, Luisenstrasse 53, 10099 Berlin, Germany","Fietz, S., Leibniz Institute of Freshwater Ecology and Inland Fisheries, Mueggelseedamm 301, 12587 Berlin, Germany; Kobanova, G., Scientific Research Institute of Biology, State University Irkutsk, Lenina 3, 664003 Irkutsk, Russian Federation; Izmesteva, L., Scientific Research Institute of Biology, State University Irkutsk, Lenina 3, 664003 Irkutsk, Russian Federation; Nicklisch, A., Institute of Biology, Humboldt University Berlin, Luisenstrasse 53, 10099 Berlin, Germany","A 3-year phytoplankton study was carried out in Lake Baikal (Siberia) as part of the CONTINENT project and in conjunction with a 60-year long monitoring programme by the Irkutsk State University. A combination of microscopy and high performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) pigment analysis was used. All over the lake, the dominant functional group (by biovolume) was the vernal diatom blooms, due to the dominance of endemic Cyclatella species. Chlorophyll a (Chl a) was significantly highest at the Selenga and Barguzin inflows (2.39 ± 0.34 and 2.49 ± 0.18 nmol L-1, mean ± 95% CI, respectively) and higher in the South than in the North (1.43 ± 0.26 and 0.96 ± 0.13 nmol L-1). This variation of Chl a reflected changes in the phytoplankton composition. Diatoms and Chrysophyceae were the major contributors to the total Chl a except in the South (Chlorophyceae) and Selenga Delta (cyanobacterial picoplankton). There were also indications of species composition changes due to enhanced P-loading from the Selenga River. However, canonical analyses indicated that temperature and stratification were the major driving forces for regional distribution patterns and seasonal succession. It seems likely that further global warming will cause a shift in the species and group composition towards small cells at the expense of the large endemic diatom flora. © The Author 2005. Published by Oxford University Press. All rights reserved.",,"community composition; community dynamics; geographical distribution; phytoplankton; seasonal variation; vertical distribution; Eastern Hemisphere; Eurasia; Lake Baikal; Russian Federation; Selenga River; World; Bacillariophyta; Chlorophyceae; Chrysophyceae; Cyanobacteria",,,,,,"Beeton, A.M., Large freshwater lakes: Present state, trends, and future (2002) Environ. Conserv., 29, pp. 21-38; Belykh, O.I., Sorokovikova, E.G., Autotrophic picoplankton in Lake Baikal: Abundance, dynamics, and distribution (2003) Aquat. Ecosyst. Health Manage., 6, pp. 251-261; Bondarenko, N.A., Taxonomic list of planktonic algae (1995) Guide and Key to Pelagical Animals of Baikal with Ecological Notes, pp. 621-630. , Timoshkin, O. A. (ed.), Nauka, Novosibirsk; Bondarenko, N.A., Floral shift in the phytoplankton of Lake Baikal, Siberia: Recent dominance of Nitzschia acicularis (1999) Plankton Biol. Ecol., 46, pp. 18-23; Bondarenko, N.A., Guselnikova, N.E., Logacheva, N.F., Spatial distribution of phytoplankton in Lake Baikal, Spring 1991 (1996) Freshw. Biol., 35, pp. 517-523; Boraas, M.E., Bolgrien, D.W., Holen, D.A., Determination of eubacterial and cyanobacterial size and number in Lake Baikal using epifluorescence (1991) Int. Rev. Gesamten. Hydrobiol., 76, pp. 537-544; Bourrelly, P., Recherches sur les Chrysophycées. Morphologie, Phylogénie, Systématique (1957) Revue Algologique, Mémoire Hors-Séries, 1, pp. 1-1